Arenas.

The arcade arena is a survival game mode, separate from building and playing maps. Instead of loading a hand-made map you drop into an endless fight against waves of enemies that never stop coming and scale up as you level. There is nothing to author here and no map file involved — you set up an arena from a few menus, pick what you want to fight, and survive as long as you can while you bank progress between rounds.

Starting an arena.

The arena is reached from the game menu, which sits on the main menu. From there you can do the following:

Load game returns to a slot you saved earlier, rebuilding the exact arena you left.
New game starts a fresh run on a slot of your choosing.

There are twenty save slots. Each one shows its total kills in the slot list, or that it is empty, so you can tell your runs apart at a glance. Choosing new game on a slot that already holds a run asks you to confirm before it erases that slot and starts over.

Once a slot is chosen for a new game you pick a mode, then what to fight, then fine-tune the field:

Normal or custom. Normal pits you against a random assortment of the enemy type you pick. Custom lets you choose one specific creature and fight endless waves of just that one. Both scale to your level.

What to fight. Animals, humans, robots, or zombies. In custom mode you then choose a single creature from that group.

The setup form.

The last step is a form that shapes the field itself:

Map mode. 2d is a side view with jumping, topdown is a bird's-eye view on a flat plane, and 3d is a full volumetric world with height. This is fixed for the run once you start.

Ambience type and volume. An optional looping background atmosphere, with its own volume. Pick none for silence.
Music type and volume. An optional looping soundtrack, with its own volume. Pick none for silence.

Tile type. The floor laid across the whole arena. Pick none for no floor.

While a type list is focused you can audition it: press space to start or stop a looping preview of the ambience or music under the cursor, or to hear a footstep of the highlighted floor tile, and the volume sliders adjust the preview as you move them.

The field.

A fresh arena starts at fifty tiles across on each axis, with the floor covering the whole area. As your level climbs the fight grows harder and more enemies are allowed on the field at once, up to a ceiling, so leveling makes each round busier rather than safer.

You can reshape the field at any time during a run with the resize keys. F1, F2, and F3 shrink, grow, and reset the maximum x reach; F4, F5, and F6 do the same for y; and F7, F8, and F9 do the same for z on 3d arenas. Each shrink or grow moves the edge five tiles, between twenty-five and a thousand, and reset returns it to fifty. The floor and the area enemies spawn in resize to match instantly. Comma, period, and slash speak the current maximum reach on each axis. See the controls topic for the full list.

Safe corners.

Every arena has two safe corners, one at your starting point and one at the far corner opposite it. Enemies can neither step into a safe corner nor spawn inside one, so each is a retreat where you can stop and catch your breath untouched. A matching carpet is laid over both corners so you can find them by the change in your footsteps, and the far corner follows the edge as you resize the field. A loaded game brings back the same carpet it had.

The shop.

Inside the arena the shop opens with shift and v, the same key as on maps, but here your purchases stay with the save slot instead of being written into your character permanently. Each run owns its own bought stats, weapon upgrades stick to each weapon and shield upgrades to each shield as you switch between them, and starting a new game on a slot truly starts from nothing.

Fighting in the arena.

Combat is tuned for the arcade pace. Enemies in the arena never break your bones the way animals and zombies can on a map, and defeated enemies only ever drop health items, since stamina is never spent in the arena.

Drawing weapons quickly.

Because macros are switched off in the arena, the macro key row is given a second job here: drawing weapons on the fly without opening the weapons menu. The row runs across the top of the keyboard — backtick, the number keys one through zero, minus, equals, and backspace — and each key draws a weapon, so you can swap between favourites in the middle of a fight without pausing.

The row draws from one weapon category at a time: whichever category your current weapon belongs to. The keys line up with that category's weapons in the same order they appear in the weapons menu, so the first key draws the first weapon in the list, the second key the second, and so on down the row. To point the row at a different category, open the weapons menu once and draw any weapon from the category you want; the row then follows that category.

There are three banks, exactly like macros, for forty two slots in all: the plain row, the row with shift held, and the row with shift and alt held together. A category with more weapons than that — and a couple of them have many more — fills the forty two slots with the first forty two of its weapons, and the rest stay reachable from the weapons menu as always. Press a slot with no weapon behind it and the game tells you the slot is empty.

Saving and loading.

Saving is manual. Nothing is banked automatically — if you quit without saving, the run is discarded. To save, open the pause menu and choose save game; it banks your run and drops you straight back into the fight. A saved run remembers your level, experience, points, kills, lives, stats, ammo, the weapon and shield in your hands and whether the shield is raised, every item you are carrying, your shop upgrades, the arena's mode, enemies, floor, music, size, and your exact position in it. Loading the slot brings all of it back.

Dying in the arena.

When you die in the arena you are asked whether to try again. Choosing yes returns you to your last saved state, exactly as if you had loaded the slot — anything you had not banked since that save is lost. If you never saved during the run, trying again starts the run over from scratch. Choosing no drops you at the game menu, where load game is one step away.
